photos.name: The Morning Still
photos.description: It's hard to find the words to describe last weekend (especially before my morning coffee kicks in)... But it was the most beautiful 3 days spent with a pile of strangers in one of the loveliest settings in the world, straight out of a fairytale and yet only a mere 20 minute flight from home. Spent a lot of time listening and observing, and left this place feeling immensely inspired by the beauty of both the landscapes and all the good human hearts and souls I was lucky enough to share this time with. Thank you. Let's keep this world beautiful. <3

photos.name: Clarity
photos.description:
I arrived in Hong Kong earlier this week just before the Typhoon hit and since then, I’ve seen the weather transform from epic clouds with super strong winds, to heavy thunder storms, sideways rain, fog, dreary flat overcast, and today as i look out my window, it’s crystal clear and calm outside. The conditions in this city can literally change from hour to hour this time of year, and honestly, that makes things really fun for photography! 

I have to admit though, this shot isn’t a result of my current time in Hong Kong. It’s actually something I shot back in 2013 and later used as one of the main lessons for my Fstoppers Photographing The World Tutorials on how I shoot and blend different moments in time together to create a unique and dramatic look in my photography. 

Sunrises like this are extremely rare, and in 2013, I invested 5 early mornings in a row to capture the illusive Hong Kong sun rising over the horizon. During the summer, it’s possible to have the most clarity in the atmosphere but it’s also extremely humid and the thunderstorms are unpredictable, so there’s never a guarantee of a quality sunrise. Overall, it’s a wonderful location and a classic example of how patience, determination, repetition, and a whole lot of coffee can make all the difference when you want to capture the right conditions for the shot. Just don’t give up and sleep in! ;)

To learn the techniques I used to shoot and post-process this image, you can find all the info about my new tutorial video series by visiting: www.fstoppers.com/elialocardi

photos.name: Trip to my inner self.
photos.description:
A trip to my inner self , These are images that I see when I dream. Then I have to remove them from within.
Nothing extraordinary but the extraordinary power that represent bringing your dreams to life. And nothing complicated, just a little imagination, patience and a small light source.

Light painting is the technique that I used for the shot; A long exposure shot (1 minute) and a small LED lantern to paint the scene with light.

You don't need tons of gear to tell stories. In fact, you just need a camera, a tripod and a lantern and yes, some imagination.

photos.name: Dream
photos.description: Two nights ago I died and went to mountain misty heaven. The moment didn't last long, and it was unexpected having just been socked in the freezing fog moments before, but you can imagine the adrenaline rush when the clouds finally broke to reveal incredible 360 degree views all around us. Immediately the next several minutes were spent sprinting full speed back and forth along cliff ledges, yelling out loud my amazement that probably consisted of many incomprehensible sounds and words and laughter, trying not to trip whilst attempting to take this self-portrait, and soaking in the views all around. "What just happened?!?!" was all we could say afterwards... I think I can safely say this was one of the best moments of my life.

photos.name: Senja Dreams
photos.description: FACEBOOK HOMEPAGE This picture is nearly as crazy as our whole journey to the Lofoten and Senja Islands the last three weeks. We drove over 7000km in sum, travelled through Austria, Germany, Denmark and Norway, came above 69° latitude and returned via Sweden and Germany. We on the one hand had days with up to 30°C sunshine with calm conditions but on the other hand it was raining cats and dogs for days. 108 hours with non stop "horizontal" rain and 18m/s storm with 6°C. 108 hours is definitely my "all-time-personal-record" and was a challenge for humor with two soaked dogs in the camper ;-). I could capture that "shot", which is a 180°+ panorama with 6 single shots, during an amazing hike on Senja Island. The "quadruple" rainbow is NOT photoshopped and it is not a stitching mistake either. A double rainbow with an additional mirrored rainbow is a quite rare phenomenon and only can evolve over calm water surfaces.

photos.name: Nadya
photos.description:
Personal online lessons and video tutorials. I will share everything I know about natural light, composition, retouching and colors. I found my own way in retouching, you will be surprised how simple it is. All you need to know is Photoshop basics (you can be an absolute beginner). I dont use frequency separation, masks and any complicated methods. It's really simple and very fast. Usually, it's only 10-30 minutes of work with one photo. And the result is good enough for covers! 

Write me by email for personal online lessons - outofsight@mail.ru
